// its a pattern we can use to check if a string looks the way we expect
// 1, Anchors
// ^ - start of string
// $ - end of string

// 2. Character Sets (Regex)
// [abc] → matches one character: a or b or c
// [A-Z] → matches any uppercase letter
// [a-z] → matches any lowercase letter
// [0-9] → matches any digit (same as \d)
// [^abc] → matches NOT a, b, or c (the ^ inside [] means not) except abc can take any letter

// 3. Shorthand Classes (Regex)
// \d → matches a digit (0–9)
// \D → matches not a digit
// \w → matches a word character (letters, digits, underscore _)
// \W → matches not a word character
// \s → matches whitespace (space, tab, newline)
// \S → matches not whitespace

// 4. Quantifiers (Regex)
// * → zero or more
// + → one or more
// ? → zero or one (optional)
// {n} → exactly n times
// {n,} → at least n times
// {n,m} → between n and m times

// 5. Special Characters (Regex)
// . → matches any single character (except newline)
// \. → matches a literal dot (.)
// \+ → matches a literal plus (+)
// \? → matches a literal question mark (?)

// 6. Grouping & OR (Regex)
// (abc) → groups "abc" together
// a|b → matches a OR b

// Once we set a regular expression, we can check or manipulate strings using:
// pattern.test(string) – quick true/false check
// string.match(pattern) – get matched text
// pattern.exec(string) – detailed match info
// string.replace(pattern, replacement) – replace matches